<LabLayout title="Lab 2: Multiplexed 7-Segment Display" labNum={2} githubUrl="https://github.com/juliacygong/E155/tree/main/lab02">
  <section>
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      In this lab, I used time multiplexing to drive two 7-segment displays using a single set of FPGA I/O pins.
      Time multiplexing was used because the anode of the 7-segment displays required more current than the FPGA
      output could provide. The dual 7-segment display takes inputs from 2 DIP switches (each 4 bits) and outputs
      the values from each. The sum of the digits is shown on a set of 5 LEDs.
    </p>

    <h2>FPGA Design and Testing Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      The design uses a clock divider that toggles frequency, a mux that selects which anode turns on, an adder
      that computes the sum for the LED display, and the 7-segment module from Lab 1.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since 60Hz is the largest frequency humans can perceive, I toggled the counter at 80Hz so the numbers
      wouldn't bleed together.
    </p>

    <h3>Hardware Implementation</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src="/images/labs/lab2/lab2_board.jpg" alt="Breadboard layout" />
      <figcaption>Figure 1: Breadboard layout of the dual 7-segment display and 5 LEDs connected to the FPGA.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Components: development board, dual 7-segment display, 5 LEDs, two 2N3906 PNP transistors, DIP switch.
    </p>
    <p>
      220Ω resistors were used to draw current from each segment. With a PNP transistor on the anodes (Vce = 200mV)
      and LED voltage drop of 1.8V: (3.3V − 0.2V − 1.8V) / 10mA = 130Ω → used 220Ω for safety.
    </p>
    <p>
      Base resistors for the PNP transistors: V = 3.3V − 0.65V, Ic = 8mA → R = 330Ω.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the LEDs (red, 2.1V drop, 10mA): R = (3.3 − 2.1) / 20mA = 110Ω → used 220Ω.
    </p>

